  "What is the definition of 'projectile motion'?": "",
  "Motion of an object launched into the air that moves under gravity alone": "",
  "Motion of an object that travels in a perfectly straight horizontal line": "",
  "Motion of an object that is propelled by a constant engine or motor force": "",
  "Motion of an object that orbits around a planet in a circular path": "",
  "Projectile motion is the motion of an object that has been launched (projected) into the air and moves only under the influence of gravity (no thrust or air resistance). It has both horizontal and vertical components.": "",
  "What does 'trajectory' mean in projectile motion?": "",
  "The path that a projectile follows through the air during its flight": "",
  "The maximum height reached by a projectile during its flight": "",
  "The initial speed at which a projectile is launched into the air": "",
  "The total time a projectile spends in the air before landing": "",
  "The trajectory is the curved path a projectile follows through the air. For projectiles near Earth's surface (ignoring air resistance), this path is a parabola.": "",
  "What does 'range' mean in projectile motion?": "",
  "The horizontal distance traveled by the projectile from launch to landing": "",
  "The maximum vertical height the projectile reaches above the ground": "",
  "The total length of the curved path the projectile follows through air": "",
  "The speed at which the projectile hits the ground at the end of flight": "",
  "Range is the total horizontal distance a projectile travels from its launch point to where it lands. For level ground, range = v0^2 * sin(2*theta) / g.": "",
  "What does 'time of flight' mean for a projectile?": "",
  "The total time from launch until the projectile returns to launch height": "",
  "The time it takes for the projectile to reach its maximum height only": "",
  "The time from when the projectile starts falling until it hits the ground": "",
  "The time required for the projectile to travel one meter horizontally": "",
  "Time of flight is the total time the projectile spends in the air, from launch to landing. For level ground, it equals twice the time to reach the peak.": "",
